01:25:10.250 --> 01:25:12.202
And I'm saying
apologies in advance

01:25:12.202 --> 01:25:13.910
to folks who are at
the back of the line.

01:25:13.910 --> 01:25:15.952
So I think we maybe take
a couple more questions.

01:25:15.952 --> 01:25:16.640
We'll go here.

01:25:16.640 --> 01:25:18.180
And then is that
Maria over there?

01:25:18.180 --> 01:25:19.552
Yeah, Maria.

01:25:19.552 --> 01:25:21.260
AUDIENCE: So this
question actually comes

01:25:21.260 --> 01:25:22.760
from our online audience.

01:25:22.760 --> 01:25:24.440
This comes from a
woman named Marcia

01:25:24.440 --> 01:25:28.280
whose family settled in
central Pennsylvania in 1737.

01:25:28.280 --> 01:25:30.523
She says her family
has many stories that

01:25:30.523 --> 01:25:32.690
have been passed down about
meeting Native Americans

01:25:32.690 --> 01:25:35.210
but she would like to
know what that atmosphere

01:25:35.210 --> 01:25:41.162
of those meetings would be
like in the early 1700s.

01:25:41.162 --> 01:25:43.120
COLIN CALLOWAY: It's
actually the kind of thing

01:25:43.120 --> 01:25:46.360
I'm really interested in.

01:25:46.360 --> 01:25:49.600
Because for all of the
brutality of the history

01:25:49.600 --> 01:25:54.120
of this continent
and colonialism,

01:25:54.120 --> 01:25:57.240
people spend a lot
of time getting along

01:25:57.240 --> 01:25:59.220
and producing children.

01:25:59.220 --> 01:26:04.440
And so there are lots
of areas and arenas

01:26:04.440 --> 01:26:10.660
where violence is not
the go to response.

01:26:10.660 --> 01:26:12.710
And in particular, I'm
thinking in Pennsylvania

01:26:12.710 --> 01:26:13.640
and Delaware country.

01:26:13.640 --> 01:26:15.800
There's a tradition
in Delaware society

01:26:15.800 --> 01:26:19.460
about these people
are peacemakers.

01:26:19.460 --> 01:26:20.630
They are intermediaries.

01:26:20.630 --> 01:26:22.190
They are diplomats.

01:26:22.190 --> 01:26:26.720
And so the initial
response to a stranger

01:26:26.720 --> 01:26:29.080
is not necessarily to kill them.

01:26:29.080 --> 01:26:32.060
And depending on
different societies,

01:26:32.060 --> 01:26:37.010
your response can be--

01:26:37.010 --> 01:26:39.380
so there are two kinds
of people in the world.

01:26:39.380 --> 01:26:43.050
There's us and other people.

01:26:43.050 --> 01:26:46.680
And other people who
are not kin and family

01:26:46.680 --> 01:26:49.350
are dangerous and
potentially hostile.

01:26:49.350 --> 01:26:50.580
Right?

01:26:50.580 --> 01:26:52.020
So, OK, you could kill them.

01:26:52.020 --> 01:26:56.040
But more often I think an
initial response is, OK,

01:26:56.040 --> 01:26:59.940
so if these people are strangers
are dangerous as strangers,

01:26:59.940 --> 01:27:02.670
how can we make
them less dangerous?

01:27:02.670 --> 01:27:07.600
By making them human, by
bringing them into our society.

01:27:07.600 --> 01:27:09.240
And that can be done
through a ritual.

01:27:09.240 --> 01:27:12.055
It can be done
through a ceremony.

01:27:12.055 --> 01:27:13.750
It can be done through adoption.

01:27:13.750 --> 01:27:16.720
It can be done through
sexual intercourse.

01:27:16.720 --> 01:27:21.140
And so I think one of the
things that we often miss--

01:27:21.140 --> 01:27:23.330
by we, I mean me--

01:27:23.330 --> 01:27:25.730
as historians looking
back over history,

01:27:25.730 --> 01:27:27.860
the light is so good
on the bloodshed

01:27:27.860 --> 01:27:30.240
and the wars, et cetera.

01:27:30.240 --> 01:27:34.340
But there's lots and
lots of places and times

01:27:34.340 --> 01:27:38.240
where people are not doing
that and they're actually

01:27:38.240 --> 01:27:40.880
intermarrying and
welcoming each other

01:27:40.880 --> 01:27:44.060
and trying to reach across
these cultural gulfs

01:27:44.060 --> 01:27:46.040
and sometimes failing.

01:27:46.040 --> 01:27:46.580
Right?

01:27:46.580 --> 01:27:49.455
And that's a huge part of
the tragedy when people

01:27:49.455 --> 01:27:50.580
are actually trying to do--

01:27:50.580 --> 01:27:53.970
if you like-- the right
thing and getting it wrong.

01:27:53.970 --> 01:27:59.890
So I've done a lot of
work looking at captives.

01:27:59.890 --> 01:28:01.540
So if you walk into
an Indian vill--

01:28:01.540 --> 01:28:04.220
I remember years ago at the
Newberry Library, Helen Tanner

01:28:04.220 --> 01:28:06.280
saying to me, Colin.

01:28:06.280 --> 01:28:08.030
Phil, if you knew
Helen, you can imagine--

01:28:08.030 --> 01:28:10.970
you will never find an
Indian village with members

01:28:10.970 --> 01:28:12.710
of only one tribe in it.

01:28:12.710 --> 01:28:14.960
And what she was
talking about was

01:28:14.960 --> 01:28:19.190
how Indian societies embraced,
adopted, and welcomed

01:28:19.190 --> 01:28:22.700
other people and increased.

01:28:22.700 --> 01:28:26.060
By the 18th century,
those other people

01:28:26.060 --> 01:28:29.400
often included white people.

01:28:29.400 --> 01:28:31.660
And this is not just
me making this up.

01:28:31.660 --> 01:28:33.880
Benjamin Franklin
worried about this.

01:28:33.880 --> 01:28:35.327
Other people worried about it.

01:28:35.327 --> 01:28:36.910
Benjamin Franklin
said, wait a minute.

01:28:36.910 --> 01:28:39.710
We're supposed to be
building a city on a hill.

01:28:39.710 --> 01:28:42.130
And we're the model
of civilization.

01:28:42.130 --> 01:28:45.220
But a lot of our own
citizens given half a chance

01:28:45.220 --> 01:28:47.510
are going off to
live with Indians.

01:28:47.510 --> 01:28:49.510
And a lot of people who
have been taken captive,

01:28:49.510 --> 01:28:53.830
given the chance to come
home, say they'd rather not.

01:28:53.830 --> 01:28:56.200
And I don't think you
do that in societies

01:28:56.200 --> 01:28:57.850
that are just violent.

01:28:57.850 --> 01:29:02.470
So there have got to be these
mechanisms for adoption.

01:29:02.470 --> 01:29:04.210
And part of captive
taking, when I

01:29:04.210 --> 01:29:07.030
look at captives that are
taking on the Connecticut River

01:29:07.030 --> 01:29:10.540
and taken up to
Abenaki country, you

01:29:10.540 --> 01:29:13.690
have the incredible violence
of a raid in which parents

01:29:13.690 --> 01:29:15.220
might be killed.

01:29:15.220 --> 01:29:19.180
And then the children would
be given little moccasins

01:29:19.180 --> 01:29:22.540
and carried on the shoulder
or pulled along on toboggans

01:29:22.540 --> 01:29:27.520
and treated with kindness as
part of the process getting

01:29:27.520 --> 01:29:33.040
them ready for adoption for
them to then become Abenaki.

01:29:33.040 --> 01:29:36.980
So you've got a cultural tussle
here that's going both ways.

01:29:36.980 --> 01:29:39.820
And sometimes what Indian
people are doing I think

01:29:39.820 --> 01:29:43.480
is meeting outsiders,
and even Europeans,

01:29:43.480 --> 01:29:45.985
with kindness rather
than violence.

01:29:45.985 --> 01:29:48.360
PHILIP DELORIA: So let's do--
we'll do one last question.

01:29:48.360 --> 01:29:50.980
Maria, kind of--
and we'll go quick.

01:29:50.980 --> 01:29:52.390
And we'll try to wrap things up.

01:29:52.390 --> 01:29:52.850
AUDIENCE: Absolutely.

01:29:52.850 --> 01:29:54.350
I'll try and keep
this really brief.

01:29:54.350 --> 01:29:56.230
I just wanted to express
a lot of gratitude

01:29:56.230 --> 01:29:57.640
for the conversation here today.

01:29:57.640 --> 01:29:59.380
It's so important.

01:29:59.380 --> 01:30:02.340
I'm speaking as a history
professor here at UMass Boston.

01:30:02.340 --> 01:30:03.940
Some of my students are here.

01:30:03.940 --> 01:30:06.430
And my question actually
is in part inspired by them

01:30:06.430 --> 01:30:10.240
but also inspired by, I think,
the very careful attention

01:30:10.240 --> 01:30:12.910
you've all brought to the
importance of doing work

01:30:12.910 --> 01:30:15.070
to change the dominant
narratives that

01:30:15.070 --> 01:30:17.410
are pervasive in so many
different ways, right?

01:30:17.410 --> 01:30:19.210
Passed down through
the generations,

01:30:19.210 --> 01:30:20.920
pervasive in our
cultural institutions,

01:30:20.920 --> 01:30:23.500
pervasive in our
education system.

01:30:23.500 --> 01:30:25.540
And my question really
comes from an experience

01:30:25.540 --> 01:30:29.830
I have in the classroom
semester after semester when

01:30:29.830 --> 01:30:33.040
my students tell me that
they never got any of this

01:30:33.040 --> 01:30:34.970
at earlier points
in their education.

01:30:34.970 --> 01:30:36.490
And so we always
have to start class

01:30:36.490 --> 01:30:38.860
with a process of unlearning.

01:30:38.860 --> 01:30:40.570
And so my question
is really I'd love

01:30:40.570 --> 01:30:43.720
to hear your thoughts about
opportunities or points

01:30:43.720 --> 01:30:46.090
for intervention
that we might be

01:30:46.090 --> 01:30:48.310
able to pursue to
kind of start changing

01:30:48.310 --> 01:30:51.397
that narrative at earlier
points in the education system.

01:30:55.053 --> 01:30:56.040
JULIA A KING: I can--

01:30:56.040 --> 01:30:56.998
PHILIP DELORIA: Please.

01:30:56.998 --> 01:31:01.560
JULIA A KING: I mean I think
that's the $64,000 question.

01:31:01.560 --> 01:31:04.620
There's a lot of parts
that are involved

01:31:04.620 --> 01:31:09.240
in doing that, beginning
with the educational system.

01:31:09.240 --> 01:31:13.380
And the way I see the groups,
the tribes, that I work with

01:31:13.380 --> 01:31:16.050
do it is a constant
raising awareness.

01:31:16.050 --> 01:31:17.370
I mean they're going out.

01:31:17.370 --> 01:31:19.020
And then I do my part.

01:31:19.020 --> 01:31:22.680
As an archeologist, they
ask me to do certain things

01:31:22.680 --> 01:31:23.970
or provide information.

01:31:23.970 --> 01:31:25.630
And I try to do that.

01:31:25.630 --> 01:31:31.920
But I almost feel like it's
one school child at a time.

01:31:31.920 --> 01:31:35.370
And so I do think it
is very challenging.

01:31:35.370 --> 01:31:38.010
I will tell you in Virginia,
I have a colleague,

01:31:38.010 --> 01:31:40.230
Martin Galvan he's
written about what's

01:31:40.230 --> 01:31:42.540
called strategic essentialism.

01:31:42.540 --> 01:31:48.660
And in this essay, he writes
about how the Virginia groups,

01:31:48.660 --> 01:31:50.910
the Virginia tribes-- which
are actually now federally

01:31:50.910 --> 01:31:53.790
recognized or many of them are--

01:31:53.790 --> 01:31:58.140
how they sort of take
those dominant narratives

01:31:58.140 --> 01:32:01.290
and try to derive
authority from them

01:32:01.290 --> 01:32:03.540
and then flip the narrative.

01:32:03.540 --> 01:32:05.430
So they get in that way.

01:32:05.430 --> 01:32:06.870
So I know we don't
have much time

01:32:06.870 --> 01:32:10.830
but that may be a
way to try to get

01:32:10.830 --> 01:32:12.720
people's attention with that.

01:32:12.720 --> 01:32:14.310
COLIN CALLOWAY: I
think that I mean

01:32:14.310 --> 01:32:16.290
it is the $64,000 question.

01:32:16.290 --> 01:32:22.500
And I get that
question or concern

01:32:22.500 --> 01:32:27.080
not only from white
students from Connecticut

01:32:27.080 --> 01:32:31.090
but from Native American
students from Oklahoma.

01:32:31.090 --> 01:32:34.000
They've got Indian symbols
on their license plates

01:32:34.000 --> 01:32:36.910
but they're not teaching
this in schools apparently.

01:32:36.910 --> 01:32:40.190
And I agree with all
of these strategies.

01:32:40.190 --> 01:32:42.250
But at some point,
it's political

01:32:42.250 --> 01:32:43.820
because I've done
a lot of workshop

01:32:43.820 --> 01:32:47.860
with teachers over the years,
high school, middle school, et

01:32:47.860 --> 01:32:49.460
cetera, from all
over the country.

01:32:49.460 --> 01:32:51.430
And they are hungry
for this information

01:32:51.430 --> 01:32:53.890
because their students are
hungry for the information.

01:32:53.890 --> 01:32:58.370
But very often, at the
end people have said,

01:32:58.370 --> 01:33:01.090
yeah, this is all
great, professor,

01:33:01.090 --> 01:33:03.700
but you're not
setting up the tests

01:33:03.700 --> 01:33:08.590
by which we are judged on how
our students are performing.

01:33:08.590 --> 01:33:10.940
And so I think this
is something where

01:33:10.940 --> 01:33:14.500
there has to come some
leadership from the top

01:33:14.500 --> 01:33:18.430
as well so that those teachers
that I see, if you like,

01:33:18.430 --> 01:33:21.010
struggling in the trenches
coming hungry for stuff

01:33:21.010 --> 01:33:25.420
that they can use in a unit in
class, but always, if you like,

01:33:25.420 --> 01:33:27.200
looking over their shoulder.

01:33:27.200 --> 01:33:27.880
All right?

01:33:27.880 --> 01:33:31.120
I can talk about the Iroquois
Confederacy and the Trail

01:33:31.120 --> 01:33:35.620
of Tears, et cetera, but
I know that my students

01:33:35.620 --> 01:33:37.640
are going to be tested.

01:33:37.640 --> 01:33:39.070
And I don't want
them to be found

01:33:39.070 --> 01:33:45.070
wanting on these other things
that educational policy

01:33:45.070 --> 01:33:49.610
makers, if you like,
say we have to have.

01:33:49.610 --> 01:33:52.793
So, yeah, I don't have
a quick answer for it.

01:33:52.793 --> 01:33:54.710
Obviously, I don't have
a quick answer for it.

01:33:54.710 --> 01:33:56.480
I haven't been able
to do it in 25 years.

01:33:56.480 --> 01:34:01.320
But I think this is
what we're dealing with.

01:34:01.320 --> 01:34:03.950
PHILIP DELORIA: And you know
as a former K-12 educator,

01:34:03.950 --> 01:34:05.780
I can say I was
handed a curriculum.

01:34:05.780 --> 01:34:08.120
I was given that
curriculum to teach.

01:34:08.120 --> 01:34:12.230
So many curricula
have been developed

01:34:12.230 --> 01:34:15.182
over the years, so many teacher
training kinds of things.

01:34:15.182 --> 01:34:16.640
I think the pressure,
my sympathies

01:34:16.640 --> 01:34:18.057
are always with
classroom teachers

01:34:18.057 --> 01:34:20.690
on the very real
challenges that they

01:34:20.690 --> 01:34:22.700
face in the classroom
around this stuff.

01:34:22.700 --> 01:34:24.530
At the same time, I
also recognize the ways

01:34:24.530 --> 01:34:28.100
in watching my own children
pass through third grade,

01:34:28.100 --> 01:34:30.890
when you got it, sixth grade
when you kind of got it,

01:34:30.890 --> 01:34:33.475
is that teachers also tend
to teach their own memories.

01:34:33.475 --> 01:34:34.850
And the third
grade teacher tends

01:34:34.850 --> 01:34:38.510
to teach what that teacher
actually remembered

01:34:38.510 --> 01:34:40.100
being taught as a third grader.

01:34:40.100 --> 01:34:42.080
It's amazing to me the
sort of reproduction

01:34:42.080 --> 01:34:44.712
that happens there, the power
of cultural reproduction.

01:34:44.712 --> 01:34:46.920
And intervening in that is
a really hard thing to do,

01:34:46.920 --> 01:34:49.450
particularly, you
know as Colin has said

01:34:49.450 --> 01:34:51.800
and Julia said, around the
restrictions that actually

01:34:51.800 --> 01:34:52.800
appear in the classroom.

01:34:52.800 --> 01:34:54.450
This is a major,
major challenge to us.

01:34:54.450 --> 01:34:57.050
And I think if I might
just say a few things

01:34:57.050 --> 01:34:57.980
by way of wrapping up.

01:34:57.980 --> 01:35:01.190
I began by saying, look,
Indian people make up 1.5%.

01:35:01.190 --> 01:35:02.750
We deserve more
of the narrative.

01:35:02.750 --> 01:35:05.360
I think this is really true.

01:35:05.360 --> 01:35:09.170
But we struggle to get
1.5% of the narrative.

01:35:09.170 --> 01:35:12.260
And until we can get
up to 10% or 15% or 20%

01:35:12.260 --> 01:35:16.550
and realize that the United
States is fundamentally about--

01:35:16.550 --> 01:35:19.070
not just slavery, because that
is the important place where

01:35:19.070 --> 01:35:21.890
schools actually have
intervened but also

01:35:21.890 --> 01:35:24.290
about Native American
history and the ways

01:35:24.290 --> 01:35:27.200
that this country is
built on a continent's

01:35:27.200 --> 01:35:28.650
worth of native land.

01:35:28.650 --> 01:35:30.890
I think this is a struggle
we have to continue to do.

01:35:30.890 --> 01:35:33.590
We do it, of course, from
a certain perspective.

01:35:33.590 --> 01:35:36.320
As academics, we find ourselves
caught up in mission creep

01:35:36.320 --> 01:35:39.540
as we try to get
into public schools.

01:35:39.540 --> 01:35:40.680
So this is hard.

01:35:40.680 --> 01:35:42.820
It's a hard challenge
and a hard problem.

01:35:42.820 --> 01:35:44.612
COLIN CALLOWAY: And it
is hard for teachers

01:35:44.612 --> 01:35:47.600
because if you're
teaching American history

01:35:47.600 --> 01:35:51.320
with due attention to, say,
Native American history

01:35:51.320 --> 01:35:55.943
and slavery in a country
where that dominant narrative

01:35:55.943 --> 01:35:57.860
that you're talking about
is so strong, and so

01:35:57.860 --> 01:36:01.550
compelling, and so satisfying
for so many people, that

01:36:01.550 --> 01:36:02.960
can be very uncomfortable.

01:36:02.960 --> 01:36:06.190
People can-- this
can be unAmerican.

01:36:06.190 --> 01:36:08.360
With people like me, that's
not a particular worry,

01:36:08.360 --> 01:36:11.113
but for a lot of people
this is a hard thing.

01:36:11.113 --> 01:36:12.530
PHILIP DELORIA:
So I think what we

01:36:12.530 --> 01:36:15.320
can agree upon is that the
work that's happening here

01:36:15.320 --> 01:36:18.200
with our guests is
contributing to the kind

01:36:18.200 --> 01:36:20.343
of ongoing questioning
of these narratives.

01:36:20.343 --> 01:36:22.010
And I hope you'll
join me in thank them.

01:36:22.010 --> 01:36:25.060
[APPLAUSE]

